"Abstract The technology of international information flows is widely understood, easily applied and generally well coordinated internationally. By contrast, legal responses to it have lacked full understanding, been fitfully applied and fragmentary in nature. The aim of this article is not to provide answers to all legal aspects of Transborder Data Flows (or TBDF) but rather to provide guidance on the types of questions to be asked in the first place. In doing so, the areas likely to give rise to practical problems, especially to users operating an international data network or intending to establish one, will be highlighted."
